I really like the Vietnamese culture and the Vietnamese people I have known.  The culture has been an example of a foreign culture joining the melting pot that has been America and influencing it in positive ways.

Last night of a fantastic 10 day break in Vietnam tonight, having travelled from HCM to Hanoi and back again. A truly fascinating country. Having learnt about the war at school I naively didn’t realise quite how much beautiful scenery etc there is to explore too.

In Vietnam, the Red River flows northward, nourishing lush rice fields. While the Mekong Delta holds vibrant markets and floating boats. Majestic mountains cradle ancient towns, showcasing the nation’s rich culture and diversity.

In Vietnam, the stunning terraced rice fields of Sapa cascade down the mountains, while the Mekong Delta thrives with life. From the bustling streets of Hanoi to the serene beaches of Da Nang, each region offers a unique charm.

Man I love the way you guys travel. A lot longer for us to cross the pond. I’ve heard from several people in the UK  Vietnam is a paradise. Resorts everywhere. Even Americans said it was the most beautiful country in the war. But is cheap and Gorgeous. How things change.

Vietnam keeps literally EVERYTHING they have ever received or captured. What’s even more beautiful is how everything is kept basically showroom new with updates done every so often. It’s beautiful seeing M-60s alongside T-54s and T-90s
I stayed in vietnam for 2 weeks at hanoi, danang and ho chi mihn, it was 100x better than thailand in every way thailand was good 10 years ago but now spoiled and expensive,
